Great question. In Appwrite, you query documents by passing an array of `Query` helpers to `databases.listDocuments()`.

### Basic pattern (JavaScript / TypeScript)

```ts
import { Client, Databases, Query } from "appwrite";

const client = new Client()
  .setEndpoint("https://<REGION>.cloud.appwrite.io/v1")
  .setProject("<PROJECT_ID>");

const databases = new Databases(client);

const result = await databases.listDocuments("<DATABASE_ID>", "<COLLECTION_ID>", [
  // Query helpers go here
]);
```

---

## 1) Filtering

```ts
const result = await databases.listDocuments(DB_ID, COL_ID, [
  Query.equal("status", ["published"]),          // status == "published"
  Query.greaterThan("views", 1000),              // views > 1000
  Query.between("rating", 3, 5),                 // 3 <= rating <= 5
  Query.search("title", "appwrite"),             // full-text search (needs index)
]);
```

- Multiple query entries are combined with **AND**.
- Multiple values in `equal()` act like **OR** for that field:
  ```ts
  Query.equal("status", ["draft", "published"]) // status is draft OR published
  ```

---

## 2) Sorting

```ts
const result = await databases.listDocuments(DB_ID, COL_ID, [
  Query.orderDesc("$createdAt"), // newest first
]);
```

You can also sort ascending:

```ts
Query.orderAsc("title");
```

---

## 3) Limiting results

```ts
const result = await databases.listDocuments(DB_ID, COL_ID, [
  Query.orderDesc("$createdAt"),
  Query.limit(10), // return at most 10 docs
]);
```

---

## 4) Pagination

### A) Offset pagination (simple page numbers)

```ts
const page = 3;
const perPage = 10;

const result = await databases.listDocuments(DB_ID, COL_ID, [
  Query.orderDesc("$createdAt"),
  Query.limit(perPage),
  Query.offset((page - 1) * perPage),
]);
```

### B) Cursor pagination (better for large/changing datasets)

```ts
// First page
const firstPage = await databases.listDocuments(DB_ID, COL_ID, [
  Query.orderDesc("$createdAt"),
  Query.limit(10),
]);

const lastDocId = firstPage.documents[firstPage.documents.length - 1]?.$id;

// Next page
const nextPage = await databases.listDocuments(DB_ID, COL_ID, [
  Query.orderDesc("$createdAt"),
  Query.limit(10),
  Query.cursorAfter(lastDocId),
]);
```

Use `Query.cursorBefore(firstDocId)` to page backward.

---

## Combined example

```ts
const result = await databases.listDocuments(DB_ID, COL_ID, [
  Query.equal("category", ["backend", "devops"]),
  Query.greaterThanEqual("likes", 50),
  Query.orderDesc("$createdAt"),
  Query.limit(20),
  Query.cursorAfter("66f2c..."), // optional
]);
```

If you want, I can also show the same query patterns in Flutter, Python, or REST format.

```js
import { Client, Databases, ID, Permission, Role } from "appwrite";

const client = new Client()
